00:50:13.456 --> 00:50:15.330
MARIO CARPO: The work
of Gaudi, Antoni Gaudi?

00:50:15.330 --> 00:50:17.940
AUDIENCE: Yes, yes-- into
this this scheme of fishes,

00:50:17.940 --> 00:50:18.990
and the dogs, et cetera?

00:50:18.990 --> 00:50:22.620
MARIO CARPO: Well, Gaudi was
a very important reference

00:50:22.620 --> 00:50:24.570
of the beginning
of a digital term

00:50:24.570 --> 00:50:27.820
in the '90s, because Gaudi--

00:50:27.820 --> 00:50:30.290
who is not a dog and not a fish.

00:50:30.290 --> 00:50:33.810
It doesn't belong to any
historical parameters,

00:50:33.810 --> 00:50:35.570
because it was a one off.

00:50:35.570 --> 00:50:39.120
It was an isolated genius,
who due to a remarkable set

00:50:39.120 --> 00:50:42.570
of circumstances was allowed
in Barcelona to make something

00:50:42.570 --> 00:50:44.010
happen, which is a miracle--

00:50:44.010 --> 00:50:46.730
which should in theory
never have existed.

00:50:46.730 --> 00:50:51.270
He wanted to reenact the way
of building of medieval master

00:50:51.270 --> 00:50:55.647
builders, so he was
building without notations.

00:50:55.647 --> 00:50:57.480
In the Middle Ages,
architectural blueprints

00:50:57.480 --> 00:50:58.620
did not exist.

00:50:58.620 --> 00:51:00.376
Craftsmens, there
was no separation

00:51:00.376 --> 00:51:02.000
between the designers
and the builders.

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:06.240
The master builders were
conceiving and making

00:51:06.240 --> 00:51:09.300
at the same time
on site on the fly.

00:51:09.300 --> 00:51:14.730
And in 1890 until 1910, Antoni
Gaudi in industrial Barcelona

00:51:14.730 --> 00:51:18.050
wanted to revive due to
his ideology, to his faith,

00:51:18.050 --> 00:51:19.770
to his inspiration--
wanted to revive

00:51:19.770 --> 00:51:22.230
the medieval way of building.

00:51:22.230 --> 00:51:23.860
He didn't want to
revive a style.

00:51:23.860 --> 00:51:27.330
He wanted really to revive
a social organization

00:51:27.330 --> 00:51:29.580
of a medieval
building site, so he

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:31.160
wanted to devise a
way of being where

00:51:31.160 --> 00:51:33.960
there's no designer
separated from the builder.

00:51:33.960 --> 00:51:36.390
The builder is a
master builder, who

00:51:36.390 --> 00:51:39.530
decides every day what
is going to build.

00:51:39.530 --> 00:51:42.760
In an industrial world,
you cannot build that way.

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:44.850
But in Barcelona,
at that time, he

00:51:44.850 --> 00:51:47.940
found illuminated
sponsor, who decided

00:51:47.940 --> 00:51:50.410
that he should build a
big cathedral that way--

00:51:50.410 --> 00:51:53.500
to the superior glory
of god, which he did.

00:51:53.500 --> 00:51:55.320
And the building
is still going on,

00:51:55.320 --> 00:51:57.210
because a medieval
cathedral, since it

00:51:57.210 --> 00:52:00.054
has no design has no
beginning and no end.

00:52:00.054 --> 00:52:02.220
So long as there is someone
who is willing to build,

00:52:02.220 --> 00:52:04.470
the building will keep growing.

00:52:04.470 --> 00:52:08.070
And as of the mid-'90s,
someone I know, Mark Burry,

00:52:08.070 --> 00:52:12.250
took on from where Gaudi stopped
using computer-aided design,

00:52:12.250 --> 00:52:15.690
because he thought with some
reason that using CAD/CAM--

00:52:15.690 --> 00:52:17.940
computer-aided design and
computer-aided fabrication--

00:52:17.940 --> 00:52:21.780
it is easier to reenact the
medieval way of building.

00:52:21.780 --> 00:52:24.210
Because if you work
with computers,

00:52:24.210 --> 00:52:27.580
you can design and make
almost at the same time,

00:52:27.580 --> 00:52:29.740
because you're using
the same machine.

00:52:29.740 --> 00:52:33.660
The same tool that puts
a picture on the screen

00:52:33.660 --> 00:52:35.760
can print it out,
so the separation

00:52:35.760 --> 00:52:38.910
between designer and
maker is compressed

00:52:38.910 --> 00:52:40.360
by the tool you're using.

00:52:40.360 --> 00:52:42.840
So in a sense, this
use of a computer

00:52:42.840 --> 00:52:46.710
is more medieval than modern,
which is why they are now--

00:52:46.710 --> 00:52:49.620
they are now still building
the Sagrada Familia

00:52:49.620 --> 00:52:53.510
using computers-- in a sense
continuing and interpreting

00:52:53.510 --> 00:52:56.100
Gaudi's dream of
reviving the Middle Ages.

00:52:56.100 --> 00:52:57.340
It's a fascinating story.

00:52:57.340 --> 00:52:59.564
Thanks for bringing it up.

00:52:59.564 --> 00:53:04.230
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
which technique Gaudi

00:53:04.230 --> 00:53:09.740
used to some sketches.

00:53:09.740 --> 00:53:14.750
I think that, even though
he built recently by himself

00:53:14.750 --> 00:53:21.100
and leads the process, he had
some drawings of cathedral.

00:53:21.100 --> 00:53:23.390
MARIO CARPO: He had
diagrams not blueprints,

00:53:23.390 --> 00:53:26.510
because stereotomy, which is the
medieval technique for cutting

00:53:26.510 --> 00:53:29.300
stone, you can not represent it.

00:53:29.300 --> 00:53:33.250
But there are ways to teach
to the artisans how to do it.

00:53:33.250 --> 00:53:35.630
And in the case of some
complicated curves,

00:53:35.630 --> 00:53:37.740
he actually used
catenary models,

00:53:37.740 --> 00:53:41.180
which we are still using,
to determine the shape

00:53:41.180 --> 00:53:43.160
of some arches and their load.

00:53:43.160 --> 00:53:45.130
And in that, he was
probably bringing

00:53:45.130 --> 00:53:48.080
in a technology which the
medieval builders would not

00:53:48.080 --> 00:53:48.600
have known.

00:53:48.600 --> 00:53:51.260
So he was probably tweaking
his own rules a little bit.

00:53:51.260 --> 00:53:55.440
But I don't think there
are drawings by Gaudi.

00:53:55.440 --> 00:53:59.510
Diagrams, yes-- sketches made
after the building has been

00:53:59.510 --> 00:54:02.150
built, yes-- but blueprint, no.

00:54:02.150 --> 00:54:04.070
Because that is contrary.

00:54:04.070 --> 00:54:05.900
It goes contrary to his spirit.

00:54:05.900 --> 00:54:07.910
A blueprint is an
instruction, which

00:54:07.910 --> 00:54:10.610
a thinker gives to a maker.

00:54:10.610 --> 00:54:12.380
In the medieval
scheme of things,

00:54:12.380 --> 00:54:14.460
that separation does not exist.

00:54:14.460 --> 00:54:16.700
If you build, you
think and make.

00:54:16.700 --> 00:54:18.980
As an artisan, you
don't have a blueprint.

00:54:18.980 --> 00:54:21.260
You don't receive a
blueprint to execute.

00:54:21.260 --> 00:54:24.050
You decide, every
day in the morning,

00:54:24.050 --> 00:54:28.170
what you will do during the
day, because that's medieval.

00:54:28.170 --> 00:54:30.680
The architectural profession,
which I described,

00:54:30.680 --> 00:54:32.720
was invented in the
Renaissance when

00:54:32.720 --> 00:54:36.140
the humanists, a bunch of snobs,
decided that designers should

00:54:36.140 --> 00:54:40.250
make and that ideas should have
an intellectual value which

00:54:40.250 --> 00:54:45.050
is superior to actual craft,
but that is a modern invention.

00:54:45.050 --> 00:54:47.540
It was invented in the 15th
century with the Renaissance.

00:54:47.540 --> 00:54:50.710
In the Middle Ages, the
separation did not exist.

00:54:50.710 --> 00:54:52.305
This is what Gaudi had in mind--

00:54:52.305 --> 00:54:54.180
to revive the Middle
Ages, because he did not

00:54:54.180 --> 00:54:58.080
like modernity even though the
money used to build the Sagrada

00:54:58.080 --> 00:55:00.990
Familia was being earned by the
modern industrial development

00:55:00.990 --> 00:55:04.517
in Barcelona, but
that's the way it works.

00:55:04.517 --> 00:55:08.500
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:08.500 --> 00:55:10.840
Thanks very much for the talk.

00:55:10.840 --> 00:55:13.420
There was a sense that
maybe in the '80s and '90s,

00:55:13.420 --> 00:55:17.860
maybe with CAD/CAM, other
technologies, or software,

00:55:17.860 --> 00:55:20.650
that some things started
to look quite similar.

00:55:20.650 --> 00:55:25.180
Like, cars started to
resemble each other.

00:55:25.180 --> 00:55:29.080
Like, an Audi looked
like a BMW or whatever.

00:55:29.080 --> 00:55:31.840
Do you think, with
AI machine learning,

00:55:31.840 --> 00:55:34.750
that there will be
more of that, or it

00:55:34.750 --> 00:55:38.567
will be that things become more
differentiated in their design?

00:55:38.567 --> 00:55:40.150
MARIO CARPO: It is
true, particularly,

00:55:40.150 --> 00:55:43.250
as you rightly point out,
in the case of car design.

00:55:43.250 --> 00:55:47.200
These kind of curves, the
splines, the mathematics

00:55:47.200 --> 00:55:51.190
was the same in the software
used by all car makers

00:55:51.190 --> 00:55:53.290
at the time, the
software was not.

00:55:53.290 --> 00:55:55.870
And each software
has its own tweaks.

00:55:55.870 --> 00:55:57.820
So I'm not
particularly an expert,

00:55:57.820 --> 00:56:02.500
but Greg Lynn, one of the--

00:56:02.500 --> 00:56:04.100
whose work I have shown--

00:56:04.100 --> 00:56:06.240
was very much interested
in car design.

00:56:06.240 --> 00:56:09.750
He's a real expert
and connoisseur.

00:56:09.750 --> 00:56:12.810
He tells-- I have no evidence
of that-- but by looking

00:56:12.810 --> 00:56:16.320
at the body of a car, he can
tell which release of a given

00:56:16.320 --> 00:56:21.550
software was used to make it,
and it is true to some extent.

00:56:21.550 --> 00:56:24.570
There are tweaks of each
software which leave traces.

00:56:24.570 --> 00:56:27.240
So sometimes you can tell
which release of Word

00:56:27.240 --> 00:56:29.580
was used to compose a certain
text, because, you know,

00:56:29.580 --> 00:56:32.280
cut and paste works in a
different way or something.

00:56:32.280 --> 00:56:37.560
So insofar as that
was the early--

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:40.650
you can do that because
there were probably

00:56:40.650 --> 00:56:43.560
25 kinds of software
being used in the '90s

00:56:43.560 --> 00:56:47.170
by all automotive
industry in the world,

00:56:47.170 --> 00:56:50.120
so if you are in that
field, you know them all.

00:56:50.120 --> 00:56:53.250
Now we are probably
moving to an environment

00:56:53.250 --> 00:56:56.250
where there is much more
and faster variations

00:56:56.250 --> 00:56:59.470
than adaptations, so
my guess is that game

00:56:59.470 --> 00:57:03.030
of recognizing the indexical
trace of the tools we're using

00:57:03.030 --> 00:57:06.314
is not going to be
that easy anymore.

00:57:06.314 --> 00:57:07.980
Because in the '90s,
there were probably

00:57:07.980 --> 00:57:10.880
25 variations of a
certain software,

00:57:10.880 --> 00:57:12.570
and now there are
probably 1,000.

00:57:12.570 --> 00:57:14.100
And then, that game is--

00:57:14.100 --> 00:57:17.370
so I think that
complexity, which

00:57:17.370 --> 00:57:19.680
is coming through artificial
intelligence tools,

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:22.380
will make this kind of
thing lexical transference

00:57:22.380 --> 00:57:26.354
of the tool into the traces
of it's use less conspicuous.

